>>25386363
Don't leave the page blank. Write out the scene to the best of your ability and return to it later during your next revision sweep. This goes for all writing; many, many authors observe that it's always better to write and hold momentum when you have it rather than stop, because you risk stultifying your progress and falling into a rut. It's very easy to get into a rhythm while writing and, upon reaching one of the scenes you've envisioned many times in your mind's eye, stop and occupy yourself with the best way to write it rather than just progress through it. Nothing you write is inatglio - you can alter and improve it to your heart's content later, but you'll first need to write it. This is why you often hear authors repeat the "just write" mantra like they're collectively operating on a single broken record.
